# Per-file content handling — overrides the host's
# core.autocrlf setting so binary fixtures round-trip
# byte-identical across Linux ↔ Windows ↔ macOS clones.
#
# Why this file exists: Git for Windows defaults
# core.autocrlf=true, which converts \n → \r\n at checkout for
# files Git's content heuristic classifies as "text". Some of
# our PDF + binary-fixture files look text-like to that
# heuristic (mostly ASCII content) and get mangled, shifting
# the byte-offset tables inside them (PDF xref offsets, PNG
# chunk CRCs, TIFF strip byte counts, …). The downstream parse
# fails with cryptic errors like:
#
#   "xref: /XRef stream: bad object id"
#
# every test that opens a fixture then explodes. Listing the
# binary extensions explicitly here is the durable fix; it
# applies regardless of the host's core.autocrlf setting.

# Document / image / font fixtures.
*.pdf       binary
*.png       binary
*.jpg       binary
*.jpeg      binary
*.tif       binary
*.tiff      binary
*.bmp       binary
*.gif       binary
*.ttf       binary
*.otf       binary

# Foundation-primitive raw-bytes corpora.
*.bin       binary
*.pixels    binary
*.cff       binary
*.cmap      binary

# Per-primitive "*.<primitive>fix" binary fixtures (round-trip
# oracle input/output pairs). One extension per primitive shipping
# a generator under tests/fixtures/<primitive>/.
*.bencfix   binary
*.ccfix     binary
*.dencfix   binary
*.pencfix   binary
*.tencfix   binary

# Byte-exact gate-test sidecars + fixtures — although several
# carry XML/text content (.xmp is XMP-metadata XML; .canonical /
# .expected hold expected canonical output text), the byte-exact
# gates compare them byte-by-byte against
# the lib's output. Any \n → \r\n conversion at checkout would
# break the comparison even when the conceptual content is
# unchanged. Treat as binary.
*.canonical binary
*.expected  binary
*.case      binary
*.xmp       binary
